## Why This Is Asked
Tests edge routing with simple feature flag logic using standard nginx capabilities, keeping it beginner-friendly while still requiring practical setup.

## Key Concepts
- nginx upstreams and map for header-driven routing
- TLS termination in docker-compose
- cross-DC networking and service naming

## Code Example
```nginx
http {
  upstream api-old { server api-old:8080; }
  upstream api-new { server api-new:8080; }
  map $http_x_feature_flag_alpha $target { default api-old; 1 api-new; }
  server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    ssl_certificate /certs/server.crt; ssl_certificate_key /certs/server.key;
    location / { proxy_pass http://$target; }
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test header-driven routing in CI?
- How would you add health checks and a safe rollback?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical ability to add non-intrusive QA in production, teaches traffic manipulation without risking user impact, and validates multi-DC deployment awareness.

## Key Concepts
- Traffic shadowing vs canary releases
- Nginx mirror and upstream configuration
- Docker-DC/edge proxy routing across DCs
- TLS edge termination and tenant isolation

## Code Example
```nginx
# Example shadow config snippet
upstream prod_api { server prod-api:8080; }
upstream staging_api { server staging-api:8080; }
server {
  listen 443 ssl;
  location /api/ {
    proxy_pass http://prod_api;
    mirror /mirror_to_staging;
  }
  location = /mirror_to_staging {
    proxy_pass http://staging_api;
  }
}
```

