## Why This Is Asked
This tests practical reasoning on per-tenant quotas, config hot-reload via Docker Config, and lightweight canary routing in a docker-dca cluster.

## Key Concepts
- Docker Config for runtime config delivery
- Lightweight sidecar pattern for per-tenant quotas
- Token-bucket rate limiting per tenant
- Canary routing and rollback

## Code Example
```javascript
// Simplified quota sidecar sketch (pseudo)
const quotas = loadYamlFromConfig('quotas.yaml');
let buckets = {};

function handle(req, res, next){
  const tenant = req.headers['x-tenant'];
  if(!tenant) return res.status(400).send('Tenant required');
  const q = quotas[tenant] || quotas.default;
  const now = Date.now();
  let b = buckets[tenant] || { tokens: q.limit, last: now };
  const elapsed = Math.max(0, now - b.last);
  b.tokens = Math.min(q.limit, b.tokens + (elapsed * (q.refillRate || 1)));
  b.last = now;
  if(b.tokens < 1){ return res.status(429).send('Quota exceeded'); }
  b.tokens -= 1;
  buckets[tenant] = b;
  next();
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test quota correctness across tenants?
- How would you handle config validation errors and rollback?

